example.p:
We use the arithmetic of limits:


  \lim_{x \to 3} 4x^2-1
  &= \left( \lim_{x \to 3} 4x^2 \right) - \lim_{x \to 3} 1
  & \text{difference of limits}

  &= \left( \lim_{x \to 3} 4  \cdot \lim_{x \to 3} x^2 \right) -  \lim_{x \to 3} 1
  & \text{product of limits}

  &= 4 \cdot \left( \lim_{x \to 3} x^2 \right) -  1
  & \text{limit of constant}

  &= 4 \cdot \left( \lim_{x \to 3} x \right) \cdot \left( \lim_{x \to 3} x  \right)-1
  & \text{product of limits}

  &= 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 - 1
  & \text{limit of $x$}

  &= 36 - 1

  &= 35

To apply the arithmetic of limits, we need to examine numerator and  denominator separately and make sure the limit of the denominator is non-zero.  Numerator first:


  \lim_{x \to 2} x & = 2 & \text{limit of $x$}

and now the denominator:
  \lim_{x \to 2} x-1
  & = \left( \lim_{x \to 2} x \right) - \left( \lim_{x \to 2} 1 \right)
  & \text{difference of limits}

  & = 2 - 1
  & \text{limit of $x$ and limit of constant}
  & = 1


Since the limit of the denominator is non-zero we can put it back together to  get


  \lim_{x\to 2} \frac{x}{x-1} &= \frac{\ds \lim_{x\to 2} x}{\ds \lim_{x \to
2}(x-1)}

  &= \frac{2}{1}

  &= 2

Since this is the limit  of a ratio, we compute the limit of the numerator and  denominator separately. Numerator first:


  \lim_{x \to 2} 2x-3
  &= \left( \lim_{x \to 2} 2x \right) - \left( \lim_{x \to 2} 3 \right)
  & \text{difference of limits}

  &= 2 \cdot \left( \lim_{x \to 2} x \right) -3
  & \text{product of limits and limit of constant}

  &= 2 \cdot 2 -3
  & \text{limits of $x$}

  &= 1


Denominator next:


  \lim_{x \to 2} x^2+5x-6
  &= \left( \lim_{x \to 2} x^2 \right) + \left( \lim_{x \to 2} 5x \right)
  - \left( \lim_{x \to 2} 6 \right)
  & \!\!\!\!\!\!\text{sum of limits}

  &= \left( \lim_{x \to 2} x \right)\cdot \left( \lim_{x \to 2} x \right)
  + 5 \cdot \left( \lim_{x \to 2} x \right) - 6

  &\hskip1.0in \text{product of limits and limit of constant}

  &= 2 \cdot 2 + 5 \cdot 2 - 6
  & \text{limits of $x$}

  &= 8


Since the limit of the denominator is non-zero, we can obtain our result by  taking the ratio of the separate limits.


\lim_{x \to 2} \frac{2x-3}{x^2+5x-6}
  &= \frac{\ds \lim_{x \to 2} 2x-3}{\ds \lim_{x \to 2} x^2+5x-6} = \frac{1}{8}

subsection.p:
It is IMPORTANT TO NOTE that it is not correct to write


\lim_{x \to 1} \frac{2x-3}{x^2+5x-6}
  &= \frac{-1}{0} = DNE


Because we can only write


  \lim_{x \to a} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}
  &= \frac{\ds \lim_{x \to a} f(x)}{\ds \lim_{x \to a} g(x) } = \text{something}


when the limit of the denominator is non-zero (see Example above).

ul.li:
Thus we have a hint that there is a common factor that we might be able to  cancel. So now we look for the common factor and try to cancel it.


  \frac{(1+h)^2-1}{h} &= \frac{1+2h+h^2-1}{h} & \text{expand}

  &= \frac{2h+h^2}{h} = \frac{h(2+h)}{h} & \text{factor and then cancel}

  &= 2+h

Thus we really have that


  \frac{(1+h)^2-1}{h}&= \begin{cases}
						 2+h & h \neq 0 \\
			\text{undefined} & h=0
						\end{cases}


and because of this


  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(1+h)^2-1}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} 2+h

  &= 2

example.p:
Compute the following limit:


  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(1+h)^2-1}{h}


If we try to use the arithmetic of limits, then we see that the limit of the  numerator and the limit of the denominator are both zero. Hence we should try  to factor them and cancel any common factor. This gives


  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(1+h)^2-1}{h}
  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{1+2h+h^2-1}{h}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} 2+h

  &= 2

Compute the following limit:


  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(1+h)^2-1}{h}


Numerator and denominator both go to zero as h\to 0. So factor and simplify:


  \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(1+h)^2-1}{h} &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{1+2h+h^2-1}{h}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} 2+h = 2

Compute the limit


  \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{x}{\sqrt{1+x}-1}


If we try to use the arithmetic of limits we get


  \lim_{x \to 0} x &= 0

  \lim_{x \to 0} \sqrt{1+x}-1 &= \sqrt{ \lim_{x \to 0} 1+x}-1 = 1-1 =0


So doing the naive thing we'd get 0/0. This suggests a common factor that can  be cancelled. Since the numerator and denominator are not polynomials we have  to try other tricks

